sec.p:
Diffraction patterns near the focus of the optical system with circular aperture and coma aberrations can be handled by analyzing the wavefront distortion of an off-axis beam (Supplementary Note 2). The objective lens is treated as an ideal lens for the model demonstration. Consider an incident collimated Gaussian beam passing through the lens of radius a and focal length f (Figure S2a). According to the Huygens-Fresnel principle, the light disturbance at an arbitrary observation point P in the vicinity of the focal point is determined by summing the contribution of each point Q located where the incident Gaussian beam intersects the reference sphere on the pupil plane29. The coma aberration function can also be expressed in the polar coordinates (ρ, θ) whose origin is the center of the pupil by Φ(ρ, θ) = ACρ3 cosθ, where AC is the coefficient of primary coma59. The complex amplitude U(P) is determined by calculating the diffraction integral over the intersection area S on the reference sphere29:
(3)
U(P)=−ik2π∬SU(Q)exp⁡(ikq)qdS \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} U(P)=-\frac{\mathrm{i} k}{2 \pi} \iint_{S} U(Q) \frac{\exp (\mathrm{i} k q)}{q} \mathrm{~d} S \tag{3} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
where k is the wavenumber, and q is the distance between points Q and P. For the incident beam with small off-axis amount involved, the inclination factor is approximated as unity and therefore is omitted in equation (3). The polar coordinates (ρ, θ) are translated to (r, φ) with the origin of which (ρ0, θ0) is situated at the beam center for convenience. The amplitude distribution of the Gaussian beam is given by AG exp(-a2R2 / ω2), where AG is constant amplitude, and ω is beam waist. Furthermore, cylindrical coordinates (u, v, ψ) are introduced to specify an arbitrary point P in the image field where ψ is the azimuth at the focal plane (x, y), the dimensionless coordinates v = ka (x2 + y2)1/2 / f = kβ (x2 + y2)1/2 and u = kβ2z. Then U(P) is given by:
(4)
U(P)=−ikAGβ22π∫02π∫01e−a2r2/ω2eikΦTOTAL(r,φ)rdrdφ \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} U(P)=-\frac{\mathrm{i} k A_{G} \beta^{2}}{2 \pi} \int_{0}^{2 \pi} \int_{0}^{1} e^{-a^{2} r^{2} / \omega^{2}} e^{\mathrm{i} k \Phi_{T O T A L}(r, \varphi)} r \mathrm{~d} r \mathrm{~d} \varphi \tag{4} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
The total phase term of ΦTOTAL is defined by combining the like terms:
(5)
kΦTOTAL(r,φ)=kΦ(r,φ)+k(q−f)=LC+L0(r)+L1(r)cos⁡2φ+L2(r)cos⁡φ+L3(r)cos⁡(φ−ψ) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{align*} k \Phi_{\text {TOTAL }}(r, \varphi) & =k \Phi(r, \varphi)+k(q-f) \\ & =L_{C}+L_{0}(r)+L_{1}(r) \cos 2 \varphi+L_{2}(r) \cos \varphi+L_{3}(r) \cos (\varphi-\psi) \tag{5} \end{align*}$$\end{document}
Define η = (L22 + L2 + 2L2L3 cosψ)1/2, tanχ = -L3 sinψ / (L2 + L3 cosψ). The integral difficulty of the intensity is simplified by expanding the exponential term exp(ikΦTOTAL) with the help of the Jacobi-Anger identity and Graf’s addition theorem, substituting the expended series in the integration, and integrating term-wise against φ. The intensity distribution of the diffraction pattern is developed in an infinite series:
(6)
I(u,v,ψ)=4k2AG2β4|eiLC∑s=0∞(−i)s∫01e−a2r2/ω2eiL0Js(L1)J2s(η)cos⁡(2s⋅χ)rdr|2 \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} I(u, v, \psi)=4 k^{2} A_{G}^{2} \beta^{4}\left|e^{\mathrm{i} L_{C}} \sum_{s=0}^{\infty}(-\mathrm{i})^{s} \int_{0}^{1} e^{-a^{2} r^{2} / \omega^{2}} e^{\mathrm{i} L_{0}} J_{s}\left(L_{1}\right) J_{2 s}(\eta) \cos (2 s \cdot \chi) r \mathrm{~d} r\right|^{2} \tag{6} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
where J is a Bessel function of first kind. The term s = 0 is taken with the factor 1/2. Tedious calculation can be avoided because four terms in this expansion would suffice to keep the intensity variation within a few percent. The simplification greatly speeds up the numerical calculation of the intensity distribution. In the numerical computation, the selection of each parameter is as close to the actual optical path configuration as possible, such as β = 1.25 for the 100× objective lens, relative beam position (ρ0 = 0.1, θ0 = 0°), and coma coefficient AC = 16π / k. The coefficient AC is proportional to the tilt angle of the beam incident on the objective, and we have chosen a more representative value here.

Applying the Huygens-Fresnel principle, the complex amplitude of point P is obtained by:


U(P)=−ik2π∬SU(Q)exp⁡(ikq)qKdS=−ikAG2π∬SKexp⁡(−a2r2/ω2)fexp⁡[ik(Φ+q−f)]qdS
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{aligned} U(P) & =-\frac{\mathrm{i} k}{2 \pi} \iint_{S} U(Q) \frac{\exp (\mathrm{i} k q)}{q} K \mathrm{~d} S \\ & =-\frac{\mathrm{i} k A_{G}}{2 \pi} \iint_{S} K \frac{\exp \left(-a^{2} r^{2} / \omega^{2}\right)}{f} \frac{\exp [\mathrm{i} k(\Phi+q-f)]}{q} \mathrm{~d} S\end{aligned}$$\end{document}



The inclination factor K is equal to 1 by assuming the angle between the normal of the primary and the secondary wavefront is small. Accordingly, the off-axis amount of the incident beam is considered to be a small value, therefore the variation of K over the integral area can be omitted. In the bespoke microscope system, the distance OP is small compared to f. Therefore, q is replaced by f in the denominator of the integrand, and k(q – f) is approximated in the Cartesian axes at O:


k(q−f)=−vρcos⁡(θ−ψ)+uβ2−12uρ2=−vrcos⁡(φ−ψ)−vρ0cos⁡ψ+uβ2−12u(r2+ρ02+2ρ0rcos⁡φ)
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{aligned} k(q-f) & =-v \rho \cos (\theta-\psi)+\frac{u}{\beta^{2}}-\frac{1}{2} u \rho^{2} \\ & =-v r \cos (\varphi-\psi)-v \rho_{0} \cos \psi+\frac{u}{\beta^{2}}-\frac{1}{2} u\left(r^{2}+\rho_{0}^{2}+2 \rho_{0} r \cos \varphi\right)\end{aligned}$$\end{document}



Combining the phase terms lead to:


kΦTOTAL(r,φ)=kΦ(r,φ)+k(q−f)=(ACkρ03−vρ0cos⁡ψ+uβ2−12uρ02)+(2ACkρ0−u2)r2+ACkρ0r2cos⁡2φ+(3ACkρ02r+ACkr3−uρ0r)cos⁡φ−vrcos⁡(φ−ψ)=LC+L0(r)+L1(r)cos⁡2φ+L2(r)cos⁡φ+L3(r)cos⁡(φ−ψ)
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{aligned} k \Phi_{\text {TOTAL }}(r, \varphi) & =k \Phi(r, \varphi)+k(q-f) \\ & =\left(A_{C} k \rho_{0}^{3}-v \rho_{0} \cos \psi+\frac{u}{\beta^{2}}-\frac{1}{2} u \rho_{0}^{2}\right)+\left(2 A_{C} k \rho_{0}-\frac{u}{2}\right) r^{2} \\ & +A_{C} k \rho_{0} r^{2} \cos 2 \varphi+\left(3 A_{C} k \rho_{0}^{2} r+A_{C} k r^{3}-u \rho_{0} r\right) \cos \varphi-v r \cos (\varphi-\psi) \\ & =L_{C}+L_{0}(r)+L_{1}(r) \cos 2 \varphi+L_{2}(r) \cos \varphi+L_{3}(r) \cos (\varphi-\psi)\end{aligned}$$\end{document}



Herein, we consider the dominating lower order coma (or primary coma) aberration. The coma aberration function can easily be expressed by Φ(ρ, θ) = ACρ3 cosθ, where the coefficient AC is proportional to the field angle (angle between the chief ray and optical axis). Further, the element is dS = a2rdrdφ. Hence, U(P) becomes:


U(P)=−ikAGβ22πeiLC∫01e−a2r2/ω2eiL0∫02πeiL1cos⁡2φeiL2cos⁡φeiL3cos⁡(φ−ψ)rdrdφ
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle U(P)=-\frac{\mathrm{i} k A_{G} \beta^{2}}{2 \pi} e^{\mathrm{i} L C} \int_{0}^{1} e^{-a^{2} r^{2} / \omega^{2}} e^{\mathrm{i} L_{0}} \int_{0}^{2 \pi} e^{\mathrm{i} L_{1} \cos 2 \varphi} e^{\mathrm{i} L_{2} \cos \varphi} e^{\mathrm{i} L_{3} \cos (\varphi-\psi)} r \mathrm{~d} r \mathrm{~d} \varphi$$\end{document}



The above integral can be expanded into an infinite series with the help of the Jacobi-Anger identity:


eizcos⁡ϕ=2∑s=0′∞iSJS(z)cos⁡sϕ
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle e^{\mathrm{i} z \cos \phi}=2 \sum_{s=0}^{\prime \infty} \mathrm{i}^{S} J_{S}(z) \cos s \phi$$\end{document}



Note the term s = 0 is taken with a factor 1/2, and we adopt this configuration in the following summation sign with a prime. Multiplying the expansions of the integrand with angle φ we get:


∫02πeiL1cos⁡2φeiL2cos⁡φeiL3cos⁡(φ−ψ)dφ=8∑s=0′∞∑s′=0′∞∑s′′=0′∞is+s′+s′′Js(L1)Js′(L2)Js′′(L3)∫02πcos⁡(2sφ)cos⁡(s′φ)cos⁡(s′′φ−s′′ψ)dφ
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{aligned} & \int_{0}^{2 \pi} e^{\mathrm{i} L_{1} \cos 2 \varphi} e^{\mathrm{i} L_{2} \cos \varphi} e^{\mathrm{i} L_{3} \cos (\varphi-\psi)} \mathrm{d} \varphi \\ & =8 \sum_{s=0}^{\prime \infty} \sum_{s^{\prime}=0}^{\prime \infty} \sum_{s^{\prime \prime}=0}^{\prime \infty} \mathrm{i}^{s+s^{\prime}+s^{\prime \prime}} J_{s}\left(L_{1}\right) J_{s^{\prime}}\left(L_{2}\right) J_{s^{\prime \prime}}\left(L_{3}\right) \\ & \int_{0}^{2 \pi} \cos (2 s \varphi) \cos \left(s^{\prime} \varphi\right) \cos \left(s^{\prime \prime} \varphi-s^{\prime \prime} \psi\right) \mathrm{d} \varphi\end{aligned}$$\end{document}



The integrand with the form of [cos(Aφ) cos(Bφ) cos(Cφ-Cψ)] is not zero only in limited cases. In addition, we introduce the Graf’s addition theorem for Bessel functions before the simplification:


Jk(η)cos⁡kχ=∑n=−∞∞Jk+n(u)Jn(−v)cos⁡nψ
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle J_{k}(\eta) \cos k \chi=\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty} J_{k+n}(u) J_{n}(-v) \cos n \psi$$\end{document}



where η = (L22 + L 2 + 2L2L3 cosψ)1/2, tanχ = -L3 sinψ / (L2 + L3 cosψ). Hence, expanding the summation and ignore the zero terms, the integral is simplified as:


U(P)=−ikAGβ22πeiLC∫01e−a2r2/ω2eiL0∫02πeiL1cos⁡2φeiL2cos⁡φeiL3cos⁡(φ−ψ)rdrdφ=−2ikAGβ2eiLC∫01e−a2r2/ω2eiL0[∑s=0′∞(−i)sJS(L1)J2s(η)cos⁡(2s⋅χ)]rdr=−2ikAGβ2eiLC∑s=0′∞(−i)s∫01e−a2r2/ω2eiL0JS(L1)J2s(η)cos⁡(2s⋅χ)rdr
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{aligned} U(P) & =-\frac{\mathrm{i} k A_{G} \beta^{2}}{2 \pi} e^{\mathrm{i} L_{C}} \int_{0}^{1} e^{-a^{2} r^{2} / \omega^{2}} e^{\mathrm{i} L_{0}} \int_{0}^{2 \pi} e^{\mathrm{i} L_{1} \cos 2 \varphi} e^{\mathrm{i} L_{2} \cos \varphi} e^{\mathrm{i} L_{3} \cos (\varphi-\psi)} r \mathrm{~d} r \mathrm{~d} \varphi \\ & =-2 \mathrm{i} k A_{G} \beta^{2} e^{\mathrm{i} L_{C}} \int_{0}^{1} e^{-a^{2} r^{2} / \omega^{2}} e^{\mathrm{i} L_{0}}\left[\sum_{s=0}^{\prime \infty}(-\mathrm{i})^{s} J_{S}\left(L_{1}\right) J_{2 s}(\eta) \cos (2 s \cdot \chi)\right] r \mathrm{~d} r \\ & =-2 \mathrm{i} k A_{G} \beta^{2} e^{\mathrm{i} L_{C}} \sum_{s=0}^{\prime \infty}(-\mathrm{i})^{s} \int_{0}^{1} e^{-a^{2} r^{2} / \omega^{2}} e^{\mathrm{i} L_{0}} J_{S}\left(L_{1}\right) J_{2 s}(\eta) \cos (2 s \cdot \chi) r \mathrm{~d} r\end{aligned}$$\end{document}



In this way, the original double integral is reduced to the summation of an infinite series of integrals. In fact, it is only necessary to take the first four terms of the summation series to obtain adequate intensity accuracy (Note 2. Figure 2). For those scenarios where precise intensity is not required, three terms will suffice. In this work, we select the first four terms to effectively calculate the intensities.

Rayleigh scattering applies to scatterers which are small compared to the wavelength of incident light. The differential scattering cross section is:
σd=932k′4V2π2(m2−1m2+2)2(1+cos2⁡θ) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \sigma_{d}=\frac{9}{32} \frac{k^{\prime 4} V^{2}}{\pi^{2}}\left(\frac{m^{2}-1}{m^{2}+2}\right)^{2}\left(1+\cos ^{2} \theta\right)$$\end{document}
This equation applies when (m – 1) is small. For larger scatterers such as bacteria, more complicated treatment is needed. We use Rayleigh-Gans approximation by introducing a form function P(θ) to correct for the interference of the wavelets scattered from different parts of the bacteria. Most bacteria with high water content have low refractive index. We estimate the refractive indices of E. coli and the RDM (EZ rich defined medium) as ns = 1.384 and nm = 1.338, leading to m = 1.034. Therefore, σd could be simplified to equation (7) in main text Methods. The total scattering cross section σ is obtained by integrating σd over the entire scattering regime:
σ=k′4V24π(m−1)2∫θminπ(1+cos2⁡θ)P(θ)sin⁡θdθ \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \sigma=\frac{k^{\prime 4} V^{2}}{4 \pi}(m-1)^{2} \int_{\theta_{\min }}^{\pi}\left(1+\cos ^{2} \theta\right) P(\theta) \sin \theta \mathrm{d} \theta$$\end{document}
An ideal OD measurement would collect none of the scattered light. However, scattered light over the cone of a few degrees could still fall on the spectrophotometer’s detector (Figure S15a, S15b). In the expression of P(θ) exists an orientation angle β indicating the ellipsoid of revolution to the direction of the incident beam. To compute for randomly oriented cells, P(θ) is averaged over all equally probable orientations from 0° to 90°. A relationship of σ proportional to V1.34 is obtained by simulating E. coli cells with typical morphology parameters at an incident wavelength of 600 nm.

Furthermore, m could be related to the dry-mass density (ρdry) of a cell, based on the assumption that ns is proportional to the cell’s dry matters:


ns=nm+ρdry∂n∂c⇒m−1=ρdrynm∂n∂c
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{aligned} & n_{s}=n_{m}+\rho_{d r y} \frac{\partial n}{\partial c} \\ & \Rightarrow \quad m-1=\frac{\rho_{d r y}}{n_{m}} \frac{\partial n}{\partial c}\end{aligned}$$\end{document}



where ∂n / ∂c is the specific refraction index increment. Generally speaking, differences in composition in cells will produce little percentage differences in ∂n / ∂c, thus ∂n / ∂c can be assumed as constant92. Consequently,


σ∝ρdry2V1.34
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \sigma \propto \rho_{d r y}^{2} V^{1.34}$$\end{document}



In turbidity measurement with incident light I0, OD is related to the transmission of light IT:


OD=log10⁡I0IT=log10⁡I0I0e−lσC=lσCln⁡10
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \mathrm{OD}=\log _{10} \frac{I_{0}}{I_{T}}=\log _{10} \frac{I_{0}}{I_{0} e^{-l \sigma C}}=\frac{l \sigma C}{\ln 10}$$\end{document}



where l = 1 cm is the optical path length of the cuvette in the spectrophotometer. In the simulation performed, the average σ is 0.713 µm2, which leads to a scaling factor of 3.1E-9 ml from C to OD600. On the other hand, the same scaling factor in the bulk experiments without changing temperature (Figure S17b) is fitted as 2.6E-9 ml, which is close to our numerical simulation. Combining the constant coefficients into α, equation (2) in main text can be obtained at the given condition. The relationship holds at low concentrations of bacteria. In dense cultures, multiple scattering events may redirect the first cell’s scattered light into the detector, and the destructive interferences between cells must be considered93,94. This causes deviations from the Beer-Lambert law. The change in cell density and size also disrupts the relationship95.

The OD equation is also related to total dry mas per ml (M = ρdryVC = MdryC) and single cell surface-to-mass ratio RSM = S / Mdry:
OD600=αρdry2V1.34C=αM[ρdryV0.34]=αRSMSV0.66M \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \mathrm{OD}_{600}=\alpha \rho_{d r y}^{2} V^{1.34} C=\alpha M\left[\rho_{d r y} V^{0.34}\right]=\frac{\alpha}{R_{S M}} \frac{S}{V^{0.66}} M$$\end{document}
For E. coli cells under a steady-state, RSM usually remains nearly constant96. In the above simulation, bacteria were modeled as ellipsoids, and explicit S / V0.66 was calculated in the wide parameter space (Note 4. Figure 1). The coefficient of variation (CV) is 5.6%, indicating a stable constant value of the ratio S / V0.66. It’s worth noting that the parameter range of the simulated cells is quite extensive to cover different types of cells97, so the CV of this ratio is expected to be much lower for a single type of cell. In short, OD600 can only be considered as a total mass indicator at steady-state.
